    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>Searching fallback disk around isolated young neutron star</prj:name>
        <prj:note>Evidences of debris disks have been found around some of the so-called ``magnetars'', a group of fascinatingly interesting astronomical objects believed to be bearing the strongest magnetic fields known to man. The 10^14-10^15 G magnetic fields of ``magnetars'' were inferred assuming the center neutron stars spin down through only dipole magnetic radiations. However, the debris disk, if massive enough, could cause extra friction to the star's spin, making an ordinarily magnetized (10^12 G) neutron star look like having much
stronger fields. ALMA is a sensitive sub-mm observatory capable of precisely measuring the mass of the debris disks and provides a unique way to unveil the nature of these disks and the true field strength of ``magnetars''.</prj:note>
