        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The sub-millimeter continuum is the best choice for observing the
fallback disks. Because the dusts in the disk are likely optically thin.
Therefore, the total mass of the disk can be estimated through the dust mass
assuming some gas-to-dust mass ratio. 
Here we choose to observe 682~GHz because in this frequency the dust emission
should still be dominated by thermal emission, but less so in lower
frequencies. Although in the Lower frequency bands ALMA has better
sensitivities, but the dust thermal emission also drops drastically.

Assuming a gas-to-dust (GTD) ratio of 100, and a dust temperature of 1000K
(as estimated for other AXPs), this observation we propose would clearly
detect a 0.001 Msun fallback disk at ~8\sigma level.
Furthermore, it is likely that the GTD ratio could be smaller, given that the
metalicity of the surrounding materials of a neutron star that just went 
through supernova could be considerably higher than normal.
Assuming a GTD ratio of 10, then the observation could detect disks of
0.0001 Msun. In either cases, a non-detection would rule out some fallback
disk models for this AXP, leaving the magnetar model the favorable explanation.

We asked for 33 min single continum observaiton in 682GHz with 2GHz bandwith for the desired sensitivity, i.e. to detect a disk of mass 1.e-3Msun with 8 sigma (&gt;5sigma just to be sure). A 1 arcsend angular resolution would be preferable for precise identification of the source's submm counterpart. No polarization is required.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
